101
00:08:52.395 --> 00:08:54.853
- No, I'm not frightened.
<i>- Good girl.</i>


102
00:08:55.940 --> 00:08:58.477
Your sparks - You said he was dead.
Hasn't he got a chute?


103
00:08:58.568 --> 00:09:01.560
Cut to ribbons. Cannon shell.
June, are you pretty?


104
00:09:02.280 --> 00:09:03.361
Not bad.

105
00:09:03.448 --> 00:09:05.985
<i>- Can you hear me as well as I hear you?
- Yes.</i>


106
00:09:06.076 --> 00:09:08.408
You've got a good voice.
You've got guts too.


107
00:09:08.495 --> 00:09:11.495
It's funny, I've known dozens of girls.
I've been in love with some of them.


108
00:09:11.539 --> 00:09:14.782
But an American girl whom I've never seen
and who I never shall see


109
00:09:14.876 --> 00:09:16.412
will hear my last words.

110
00:09:16.503 --> 00:09:18.665
That's funny. It's rather sweet.

111
00:09:19.214 --> 00:09:22.047
June, if you're around
when they pick me up,


112
00:09:22.133 --> 00:09:23.623
turn your head away.

113
00:09:24.886 --> 00:09:28.129
Perhaps we can do something, Peter.
Let me report it.


114
00:09:28.223 --> 00:09:31.682
<i>No, no one can help. Only you.
Let me do this in my own way.</i>


115
00:09:31.768 --> 00:09:34.726
<i>I want to be alone with you, June.
Where were you born?</i>


116
00:09:35.897 --> 00:09:37.103
<i>- Boston.
- Mass?</i>


117
00:09:37.190 --> 00:09:38.021
Yes.

118
00:09:38.108 --> 00:09:40.099
That's a place to be born.
History was made there.


119
00:09:40.193 --> 00:09:42.393
Are you in love with anybody?
No. No, don't answer that.


120
00:09:43.029 --> 00:09:44.645
I could love a man like you, Peter.

121
00:09:44.739 --> 00:09:46.980
I love you, June.
You're life, and I'm leaving you.


122
00:09:47.075 --> 00:09:48.486
Where do you live, on the station?

123
00:09:48.576 --> 00:09:51.409
No, in a big country house
about five miles from here.


124
00:09:51.496 --> 00:09:52.986
- Lee Wood House.
- Old <i>house?</i>


125
00:09:53.081 --> 00:09:54.196
Yes, very old.

126
00:09:54.290 --> 00:09:56.201
Good. I'll be a ghost
and come and see you.


127
00:09:56.292 --> 00:09:58.979
You're not frightened of ghosts, are you?
It would be awful if you were.


128
00:09:59.003 --> 00:10:01.961
<i>- I'm not frightened.
- What time will you be home?</i>


129
00:10:02.048 --> 00:10:03.755
Well, I'm on duty till 6:00.

130
00:10:03.842 --> 00:10:06.925
I have breakfast in the mess
and then I have to cycle half an hour.


131
00:10:07.011 --> 00:10:09.002
I often go along the sands.

132
00:10:09.973 --> 00:10:11.589
This is such nonsense.

133
00:10:11.683 --> 00:10:13.674
No, it's not.
It's the best sense I ever heard.


134
00:10:13.768 --> 00:10:16.886
I was lucky to get you, June.
It can't be helped about the parachute.


135
00:10:16.980 --> 00:10:19.062
I'll have my wings soon anyway.
Big white ones.


136
00:10:19.149 --> 00:10:22.232
I hope they haven't gone all modern.
I'd hate to have a prop instead of wings.


137
00:10:22.735 --> 00:10:25.727
<i>What do you think the next world's like?
I've got my own ideas.</i>


138
00:10:25.822 --> 00:10:26.653
Oh, Peter.

139
00:10:26.739 --> 00:10:29.718
I think it starts where this one leaves off
or where this one could leave off


140
00:10:29.742 --> 00:10:32.609
if we'd listened
to Plato and Aristotle and Jesus.


141
00:10:32.704 --> 00:10:36.572
With all of our little earthly problems solved,
but with greater ones worth the solving.


142
00:10:36.666 --> 00:10:39.374
I'll know soon enough anyway.
I'm signing off now, June.


143
00:10:39.460 --> 00:10:40.950
Good-bye! Good-bye, June!

